            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nWe recommend studying the previous texts in this section before proceeding with this one",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b5efc8f9-c268-430f-9681-7a43848ee48e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Primeiros pasos",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen we learn a new concept and recognize its potential usefulness in various situations, we often create tables to simplify recall—much like the scientific method does",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9a82e769-0cf6-4b17-8b98-63f27de3123e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Scientific Method",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "Having these tables readily available for quick reference is helpful, but they only become meaningful when we understand how they were constructed. In this text—and in those that follow—we will explore what multiplication tables are and the insights they provide, rather than simply memorizing them.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_why",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Why do we need a table?\n\nThe word \"multiply\" also means increasing, which directly relates to everything we have discussed so far",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "8f3ff01f-f512-47ba-9a0d-cb3cac79cc3e",
                     "text": "Cambridge Dictionary",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Family\n\nIn familial generations—like those depicted on Altar Q in Copán, Honduras—when a child is born, we say the family \"is multiplying\" (meaning the number of people is increasing).",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlides\"></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\">Slide 1: Images of Altar Q at the archaeological site of Copán, Honduras. Photo taken during a visit on <htdate0>.<br />The names of the kings (<i>ajawob</i>) are detailed in the work of Anastasia Hutnick (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('85c2d88c-6ad8-4858-95f8-0f157c49bf07'); return false;\">Hutnick, Anastasia, <htdate1>, pp. 18, 35 - 67.</a>).<br />The slide's source code was inspired by a template from (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('cf7adc72-d340-412e-8d48-953ac64cb670'); return false;\">W3Schools</a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "4",
                     "day": "26"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2020",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The altar is shaped like a big box, with inscriptions on top and sculpted human figures on its sides.",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Forest\n\nAnother example of multiplication is forests, such as those near Teotihuacán.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgTeotihuacanGeneral\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgTeotihuacanGeneral', '0%')\" src=\"images/TeotihuacanGeneral.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 1: General view of Teotihuacán. Photo taken on <htdate0> during a visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "General view of Teotihuacan city. In this photo it is possible to observe different constructions in format \"Talud-Tablero\", and in the background we have pyramidal structures representing sacred moutains.",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Simplifying\n\nBefore proceeding, let’s reflect:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Simplifying</b><br /><br />For families, we multiply people.<br />For forests, we multiply trees.<br /><br />Can we count them in the same way?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "In both cases—people and trees—we are counting living beings. Therefore, the counting method is the same for both. With this understanding, we can build a results table.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_zero",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Multiplication by Zero (0)\n\nWith the numbers we learned, zero (0) is the first number employed in counting, representing the concept of emptiness. Based on this idea, we will begin our multiplication table with it",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "576e4648-77fa-4a6d-9e51-9459ced964f3",
                     "text": "Musa, Auwalu",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b1a262fc-0148-489b-8b70-5266a85c1e67",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Visualizing the multiplication\n\nLet us conduct a small experiment using Table 1:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"ht-grid-container\"  style=\"background-image: url('images/CaralPiramideH1.jpg'); width: 100%; background-size: cover; background-position: center; background-repeat: no-repeat; margin: auto;\"><div>1</div><div>2</div><div>3</div><div>4</div><div>5</div><div>6</div><div>7</div><div>8</div><div>9</div><div>10</div><div>11</div><div>12</div><div>13</div><div>14</div><div>15</div><div>16</div><div>17</div><div>18</div><div>19</div><div>20</div></div></p><p class=\"desc\">Table 1: Pyramid H1 at the archaeological site of Caral (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('720f6dfd-4b86-4e07-a887-1010e1041a4d'); return false;\">Ruta Caral, <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('03c3743c-d268-4730-ba8e-d36b5c49e781'); return false;\">Youtube - Caral Perú Oficial, <htdate0></a>). Photo taken on <htdate1> during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1: Multiplying by Zero</b><br />The numbered rectangles in the table represent groups used to sum the elements inside them. For example, suppose we are counting people within each rectangle.<br /><br />Upon close observation, we conclude that there are no people inside any of the rectangles. Therefore, the total number of people in the first row is calculated as follows:<br />Total people = 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 = 4 x 0 = 0<br /><br />If we expand the count to the first two rows, the result remains the same:<br />Total people = 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 = 8  x 0 = 0</div></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "This experiment leads us to conclude that, regardless of the number of rectangles considered, the total number of people does not change, since there are no people in Table 1. The same would apply if we were counting trees or any other object absent from the image.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Constant Result</b><br /><br />Given these results, what is the outcome when any number is multiplied by zero?<br /><br />We can rephrase the reflection as follows:<br /><br />Is it possible to find something in a place where that thing does not exist?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Constructing a Multiplication Table\n\nDuring Practice 1, when performing multiplication, we used the following formula:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 1: This formula is used in Calculation 1 to represent repeated sums of zero elements in a group.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "In this formula:\n- The Result (left side of the equation) is known as the product of multiplication.\n- On the right side are the factors, where N represents the number identifying the group in Table 1",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "79d126c9-39ac-4679-904b-4ab69558e44e",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p>Applying Formula 1 to the first 10 groups in Table 1, we obtain the following multiplication table for zero (0):</p><p><div style=\"border-radius: 30px; margin: auto; border-style= solid; background-color: lightblue; width: 30%; text-align: center\">Multiplication Table of 0<br /><br /><math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>0</mi> </math><br /><math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>1</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>2</mi></math><br /> <math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>3</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>4</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>5</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>6</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>7</mi> </math><br /><math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>8</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>9</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>0</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>10</mi> </math></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Graphical Representation of the Table\n\nAnother way to visualize and understand these results is through graphical representation. Before proceeding, let us reflect:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: What does this suggest to you?</b><br /><br />When observing the values in the Multiplication Table of 0, what image comes to mind?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "To graphically represent these values, we recall the relationship between numbers and a number line",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0713ca05-8889-427b-802e-f2d31f045c09",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"chart\"><div class=\"tick\"><span>0</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>1</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>2</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>3</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>4</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>5</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>6</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>7</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>8</span></div><div class=\"tick\"><span>9</span></div><div class=\"tick arrow rightarrow\"></div></div></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 1: Numerical Axis. The numbers are arranged below a line, with an arrow at the end indicating the direction of increasing values. The CSS code used for this image is available on <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('c7edc93c-0a41-4753-8f89-9e52904ff003'); return false;\">W3 Schools</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "This line with an arrow, shown in Chart 1, is known in mathematics as an axis. We will use it to plot our table values, employing two axes:\n- Vertical Axis (Product): Displays the results.\n- Horizontal Axis (Factors): Contains the values of N (from Formula 1).\n\nOur objective is to plot, for each value of N, its corresponding result (0) on the plane. Here's how",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart1\" class=\"htChart\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 2: Points from the Multiplication Table of cero. Chart created using <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "In Chart 2, the values from the Table of 0 are represented as points on a Cartesian plane with two axes. To plot them, we follow these steps:\n- Locate the result (0) on the vertical axis (Product). Since the result is always zero, all points will lie on the zero (0) line.\n - Move along the horizontal axis (Factors) until reaching the value of N, then mark a point (circle) at the intersection.\n\nConnecting all the points forms a straight line, as shown in Chart 3:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart2\" class=\"htChart\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 3: Connected Points Forming a Straight Line. Chart created using <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_one",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Multiplication by One (1)\n\nAll principles applied to multiplication by zero also apply when multiplying by one (1) and any other number, though the results will differ.\n\n#### Understanding Multiplication by One\n\nA practical example of multiplication by one is counting by raising fingers one at a time. Use the arrows in Table 2 to visualize this concept:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"tawapukllay\" id=\"tblHandsCounting\"><tr><th>Left Hand</th><th>Right Hand</th><th>Arrows</th></tr> <tr id=\"tr0\"><td><img id=\"lefthand\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('lefthand', '0%') src=\"images/0Left_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td><img id=\"righthand\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('righthand', '0%') src=\"images/0Right_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td style=\"background-color: white;\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp0\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\"style=\"font-size:4em;color:#00f;\" id=\"traineeDown0\"></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\">Table 2: Examples of counting and multiplication by 1.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Multiplication Table Explained\n\nMultiplying a number by one is equivalent to repeatedly adding one until reaching that number. This means the result always equals the original number, except when multiplying zero, as previously noted",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7a9c733b-ca13-40f5-8849-19012540b028",
                     "text": "Ernst, Dana.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2014",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "We can summarize this concept with Formula 2",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>N</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>1</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 2: Result of multiplication by one, except when N equals zero.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
